# Functional Components ùëì

The modern standard.

A component is just a Javascript function that returns JSX.

```jsx
function Welcome(props) {
  return <h1>Hello, {props.name}</h1>;
}

// Or Arrow syntax
const Welcome = ({ name }) => <h1>Hello, {name}</h1>;
```

# Class Components üèõÔ∏è

The older way (pre-Hooks). Still good to know for legacy code.

```jsx
class Welcome extends React.Component {
  render() {
    return <h1>Hello, {this.props.name}</h1>;
  }
}
```
Must extend `React.Component` and have a `render()` method.

# Composition vs Inheritance üß©

React favors composition.

Instead of extending classes, we wrap components inside others.

```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <Layout>
      <Sidebar />
      <Content />
    </Layout>
  );
}
```

# Children Prop üë∂

A special prop that contains whatever you put *between* the opening and closing tags of a component.

```jsx
function Box(props) {
  return <div className="box">{props.children}</div>;
}

// Usage
<Box>
  <p>I am inside the box!</p>
</Box>
```

# PropTypes üõ°Ô∏è

Runtime type checking for props (before TypeScript took over).

```jsx
import PropTypes from 'prop-types';

Greeting.propTypes = {
  name: PropTypes.string
};
```
Ensures you pass the correct data type.

# Default Props üè∑Ô∏è

Values to use if no prop is passed.

```jsx
function Button({ color = "blue", text }) {
  return <button className={color}>{text}</button>;
}

// Usage
<Button text="Click Me" /> // color will be "blue"
```

# Component Tree üíª

